# Fluff Date: 2026-03-04 14:19:26
<overview>
<p>The Aeron Strike VTOL is Brooks Incorporated's entry into the post-Jihad combat VTOL market, introduced from the Duchy of Andurien in 3082. The design traces its lineage to a Word of Blake prototype program begun two decades earlier, which attempted to replace conventional rotors with vectored thrust engines to improve VTOL survivability on the battlefield. When the Word shelved the program after prototypes failed to deliver expected results during the Jihad, the concept might have vanished permanently. Instead, Brooks Incorporated acquired the surviving technology and plans from Michaelson Heavy Industries during the chaos following Operation SCOUR and brought the concept to production. The result is a fast, costly VTOL built around precision engagement at long range, positioning it well above the typical scout or infantry support role occupied by most light VTOLs. Its capabilities have generated significant demand across the Inner Sphere and beyond, though complications surrounding its targeting technology have shaped which buyers Brooks is willing to supply with the primary version.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Aeron replaces the internal combustion engine used by its Hawk Moth ancestor with a Nissan 160 XL fusion engine, more than doubling operating cost but granting cruise speed equivalent to the Hawk Moth's maximum flank speed. This exceptional velocity allows the Aeron to dictate engagement range under virtually any tactical circumstance. The primary weapon is a Hellion-a III extended-range large laser, chosen specifically to exploit that speed advantage by enabling engagement well beyond effective return-fire range from most opponents. A targeting computer enhances accuracy further, allowing pilots to place fire precisely against light and medium armored targets at distances where responses are limited.</p><p>Defensively, the Aeron relies on a layered approach: raw speed as primary protection, over three tons of Durallex Super Heavy ferro-fibrous armor providing physical resilience considerably above the standard for a 25-ton VTOL, and a Guardian ECM suite to degrade enemy targeting systems and complicate incoming fire. Together these elements create a platform that is difficult to fix in place and expensive to kill at the ranges it prefers to engage.</p><p>The targeting computer has created a persistent legal dispute with the Federated Suns, which maintains proprietary claims over the technology it alleges the Word of Blake first stole and Brooks subsequently copied. The suit's prospects are generally considered poor given how widely similar technology has proliferated, but Brooks has chosen to restrict primary variant sales to specific clients rather than court prolonged litigation over the design's most effective feature.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>Introduced exclusively to the Duchy of Andurien's military in 3082, the primary Aeron remained unavailable outside Andurien for its first two years of production. When Brooks opened broader sales in 3084, they restricted this version to the Republic of the Sphere and the Duchy of Andurien, citing the ongoing Federated Suns legal dispute over targeting computer technology. Andurien formations deploy it as a precision fire support platform, exploiting its speed and standoff accuracy to destroy light armor and harass BattleMechs from advantageous range. Republic forces use it in screening and reconnaissance-in-force roles, pairing its ECM capability with its long-range strike power. Federated Suns units have taken to field refitting BAP variants with locally produced targeting computers, bypassing the sales restriction through technical means rather than commercial channels.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Aeron's origins lie with the Word of Blake's propulsion research programs of 3062, when Blakist engineers converted a Hawk Moth VTOL into a test platform for vectored thrust technology. The goal was to eliminate conventional rotor assemblies, which experience had shown were vulnerable to battle damage and difficult to repair under field conditions. Early testing showed promise, and prototypes participated in the Jihad's opening campaigns, including engagements during the fighting for Outreach. The hoped-for durability improvements, however, failed to materialize under sustained combat conditions, and the program's costs proved difficult to justify against limited results. The Word shelved the project and redirected Andurien-area manufacturing resources toward converting Cyrano VTOL production to the Royal variant.</p><p>The surviving prototype units and their design documentation passed through multiple ownership changes during the disorder following Operation SCOUR. Brooks Incorporated tracked the technology's path and acquired the program assets, including the original vectored thrust blueprints, from Michaelson Heavy Industries as that company struggled financially in the post-Jihad environment. Brooks' engineers resolved the remaining performance problems that had plagued the Blakist design and introduced the Aeron to the market in 3082 from their Andurien facility.</p><p>The Duchy of Andurien's military was the sole customer for the initial production run, deploying Aerons across all their combat formations. The design established its combat reputation quickly: in late 3082 a Capellan Confederation raiding force struck El Giza hoping to expand their border in the vacuum between the Duchies of Oriente and Andurien, only to encounter the Fourth Andurien Cavalry and the terms of Andurien's mutual defense treaty with the Mosiro Archipelago. A lance of Aerons, repositioned into the Capellans' projected landing zone, used broken terrain to conduct hit-and-run attacks against the light BattleMech company, destroying several machines and driving the survivors into an ambush. No Capellan BattleMechs reached the waiting DropShip.</p><p>This exclusive Andurien arrangement lasted until 3084, when Brooks opened broader sales after an aggressive marketing campaign featuring combat footage from a failed Regulan assault on Andurien positions generated widespread demand. Purchase orders arrived from across the Inner Sphere, including buyers operating in former Hell's Horses territory using Diamond Shark intermediaries as procurement brokers. Brooks responded by establishing a tiered sales structure: the primary version with its targeting computer is available only to the Republic of the Sphere and the Duchy of Andurien, while all other buyers receive the less expensive BAP variant.</p>
</history>

